               Semiconducting materials that are synthesized by mixing elements from the groups IIIa and Va of the periodic table are known as the III–V compound semiconductors. These compounds could be binary, ternary, quaternary, pentenary, or higher orders depending on the number of elemental species used for synthesizing the compounds. III–V compounds have found widespread applications in electronic, optoelectronic, and photovoltaic devices. In the majority of the applications, binary compounds are used as substrate material onto which ternary or quaternary compounds are epitaxially grown as thin layers for fabricating the device structures. The substrate materials are grown in the form of bulk single crystals from high-temperature melts. With binary substrates, only a handful of lattice parameters and band gaps are possible, thus limiting the device designs and architectures. Ternary substrates provide variable band gaps and lattice constants that are necessary for advancing the next generation of device research and development. However, the ternary substrate technology is still in its early stages with limited availability for niche applications. This chapter presents an overview of the technologies established for growing high-quality binary III–V crystals and the ongoing development of ternary crystal growth technologies. Infrastructure needed for overcoming the challenges during the crystal growth of large diameter and compositionally homogeneous bulk ternary III–V semiconductors will be discussed. This chapter focuses on the (AlGaIn)–(PAsSb)-based III–V compounds. The salient features of the compound preparation and the bulk growth methodologies have been summarized.
